      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "The threshingfloor",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": precisely the same word as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:18; 2 Samuel 24:21; 2 Samuel 24:24",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 24:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 24:21",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 24:24",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Threshingfloors were constructed on eminences, to catch the wind for winnowing the grain. Araunah’s threshingfloor was on Mount Moriah, the hill to the eastward of Jerusalem, and was the site upon which the Temple was afterwards built (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 3:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). See Additional Note VI. p. 240. This Mount Moriah was identified by Jewish tradition (e.g. Josephus ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ant.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " VII. 13. 4) with the mountain in the land of Moriah which was the scene of the sacrifice of Isaac (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 22:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ff.), but the identification has been questioned. See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Sinai and Pal.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " p. 251.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "It has been supposed by some that the sacred rock of the Moslems, which is the highest point of the Temple hill, and is now covered by the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Kubbet es Sakhrah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or “Dome of the Rock,” marks the actual site of Araunah’s threshing-floor. See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Sinai and Pal.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " p. 178 ff.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Araunah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The name is variously spelt Aravnah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:16",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 24:16",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Qrî",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Avarnah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:16",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 24:16",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Kthîbh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Aranyah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:18",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 24:18",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Kthîbh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); in Chron. it is written Ornan; and in the Sept. in both books “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ὄρνα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Orna",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This variety of form is probably due to different attempts to represent a non-Hebraic name. There is no ground for the popular belief (based on a misunderstanding of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:23",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 24:23",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") that Araunah was the old king of Jebus before its conquest by David, and had been permitted by David to reside on his estate just outside Jerusalem. But his presence there is an evidence that the old inhabitants had been allowed to remain, and even to retain their property. Cp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 9:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 16.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The angel.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " In the next verse we are told that David saw the angel, and more fully in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 21:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that he beheld him \"standing between the earth and the heaven, having a drawn sword in his hand.\" The pestilence plainly was not a natural visitation; though possibly the means used was a simoom, or poisonous wind, advancing with terrible rapidity throughout Israel. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The Lord repented.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " In all the dealings of God's providence, his actions are made to depend upon human conduct. Looked at from above, from God's side, all things are foreknown and immutably fixed; looked at from man's side, all is perpetually changing as man changes. The rescue of Jerusalem as the result of David's penitence and prayers, is thus to human view a change in the counsels and even in the feelings of him who changeth not. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The threshing place.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"The threshing floor,\" as rightly translated in vers. 18, 21, 24. Threshing floors were constructed, whenever possible, on eminences, that the wind might drive the chaff and dust away. Araunah's was on the east of Jerusalem, outside the walls, upon Mount Moriah, and was the site on which the temple was built (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 3:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Araunah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The name is so spelt seven times in vers. 20-24, for which reason the Massorites have substituted it for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Avarnah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", found in this verse in the Hebrew text, and for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Aranyah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in ver. 18. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the name is spelt ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Ornan",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; in the Septuagint in all places, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Ὀρνά",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Orna",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and in the Syriac, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Oron.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The name is, of course, a Jebusite word, and the variation arises from the narrators having written down the sound as it caught their ears. In this, as in many other particulars, it is clear that the chronicler derived his account from independent Sources. 2 Samuel 24:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The general statement as to the divine judgment and its terrible effects is followed by a more minute description of the judgment itself, and the arrest of the plague. \"When the destroying angel ('the angel' is defined immediately afterwards as 'the angel that destroyed the people') stretched out his hand towards Jerusalem to destroy it, Jehovah repented of the evil (for this expression, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 32:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 26:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 26:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; and for the repentance of God, the remarks on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 6:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and He commanded the angel, Enough! stay now thine hand.\" This implies that the progress of the pestilence was stayed before Jerusalem, and therefore that Jerusalem itself was spared. \"And the angel of Jehovah was at the threshing-floor of Aravnah the Jebusite.\" These words affirm most distinctly that the destroying angel was visible. According to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", David saw him there. The visible appearance of the angel was to exclude every thought of a natural land plague. The appearance of the angel is described more minutely in the Chronicles: David saw him standing by the threshing-floor of Aravnah between heaven and earth with a drawn sword in his hand, stretched out over Jerusalem. The drawn sword was a symbolical representation of the purpose of his coming (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 22:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 5:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The threshing-floor of Aravnah was situated, like all other threshing-floors, outside the city, and upon an eminence, or, according to the more precise statement which follows, to the north-east of Zion, upon Mount Moriah (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). According to the Chethib of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the name of the owner of the floor was האורנה, of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ארניה, and of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (twice) ארונה. This last form also occurs in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and has been substituted by the Masoretes as the Keri in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In the Chronicles, on the other hand, the name is always written ארנן (Ornan), and hence in the Septuagint we find Ὄρνα in both texts. \"The form ארונה (Aravnah) has not a Hebrew stamp, whereas Orna and Ornan are true Hebrew formations. But for this very reason Aravnah appears to be derived from an ancient tradition\" (Bertheau).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]